C","icon":"","description":"Type of motion: pitching, heaving or surging (or combinations thereof?)\nShape of Device, Size, and Orientation\nSubmergence level: Floating, Partially or Fully Submerged\nLocation: Shallow, Intermediate, or Deep Waters\nIs it a mobile or fixed/coastal-structure-integrated (CSI) WEC?\nPower-Take-Off (PTO) System: Hydraulic/pneumatic/Direct-drive/Other? ","aliases":[],"inlineTags":[],"frontmatterTags":[],"headers":[],"links":[],"author":"","coverImageURL":"","fullURL":"key-components-and-working-principles-of-a-wec.html","pathToRoot":".","attachments":[],"createdTime":1778599908150,"modifiedTime":1778600012581,"sourceSize":356,"sourcePath":"Key Components and working principles of a WEC.md","exportPath":"key-components-and-working-principles-of-a-wec.html","showInTree":true,"treeOrder":10,"backlinks":[],"type":"markdown"},"power-take-off-principles.html":{"title":"Power Take Off Principles","icon":"","description":"<img alt=\"fig_typesPowerTakeOff.png\" src=\"fig_typespowertakeoff.png\" target=\"_self\">","aliases":[],"inlineTags":[],"frontmatterTags":[],"headers":[],"links":[],"author":"","coverImageURL":"fig_typespowertakeoff.png","fullURL":"power-take-off-principles.html","pathToRoot":".","attachments":["fig_typespowertakeoff.html"],"createdTime":1778600057047,"modifiedTime":1778600904131,"sourceSize":30,"sourcePath":"Power Take Off Principles.md","exportPath":"power-take-off-principles.html","showInTree":true,"treeOrder":11,"backlinks":[],"type":"markdown"},"some-historical-information.html":{"title":"Some Historical Information","icon":"","description":"\nThe concept appeared first (formally) in 1799 by Pierre-Simon Girard in France—First Patent.\nThe first documented conversion of wave energy into electricity occurred in 1909 in California.\nThe first Oscillating Water Column (OWC) was built around 1910 by M. Bochaux-Praceique near Bordeaux in France.\nThe first successful attempt at using wave power to produce electricity took place in 1947 by Yoshio Masuda in Japan\nThe idea of wave energy as a viable commercial sector gained significant momentum in the 1970s and onwards….\n","aliases":[],"inlineTags":[],"frontmatterTags":[],"headers":[],"links":[],"author":"","coverImageURL":"","fullURL":"some-historical-information.html","pathToRoot":".","attachments":[],"createdTime":1778598458304,"modifiedTime":1778598516762,"sourceSize":540,"sourcePath":"Some Historical Information.md","exportPath":"some-historical-information.html","showInTree":true,"treeOrder":12,"backlinks":[],"type":"markdown"},"there-is-an-enormous-amount-of-energy-in-the-ocean.html":{"title":"There is an Enormous Amount of Energy in the Ocean","icon":"","description":"The estimated exploitable US wave energy is about 2,640 Terrawatt-hours per year (EPRI (2011), Mapping and Assessment of the United States Ocean Wave Energy Resource). This is nearly more than half the total annual electricity demand, which is about 4,000 TW/yr (EIA, ?year?). &lt;insert questions that motivate reading EPRI or thinking about exploitable means&gt; ","aliases":[],"inlineTags":[],"frontmatterTags":[],"headers":[],"links":[],"author":"","coverImageURL":"","fullURL":"there-is-an-enormous-amount-of-energy-in-the-ocean.html","pathToRoot":".","attachments":[],"createdTime":1778598517189,"modifiedTime":1778598992779,"sourceSize":369,"sourcePath":"There is an Enormous Amount of Energy in the Ocean.md","exportPath":"there-is-an-enormous-amount-of-energy-in-the-ocean.html","showInTree":true,"treeOrder":13,"backlinks":[],"type":"markdown"},"ways-to-classify-wave-energy-converters-(wecs).html":{"title":"Ways to classify wave energy converters (WECs)","icon":"","description":"<img alt=\"fig_classByOrientation.png\" src=\"fig_classbyorientation.png\" target=\"_self\">\nBirds eye view <br><img alt=\"fig_classByOrientation2.png\" src=\"fig_classbyorientation2.png\" target=\"_self\"><br><img alt=\"fig_classByMode.png\" src=\"fig_classbymode.png\" target=\"_self\">","alia